09334nam a22011535i 9783110629460DE-B159720210621102733.0m|||||o||d||||||||cr || ||||||||210621t20192019gw     fo  d z      eng d  a2019941310  a97831106294607 a10.1515/97831106294602doi  a(DE-B1597)502161  a(OCoLC)1121054770  aDE-B1597bengcDE-B1597erda0 aeng  agwcDE 4aP301.5.M48bC87 2019 7aLAN0090002bisacsh04a401/.4322300aCurrent Approaches to Metaphor Analysis in Discourse /ced. by Ignasi Navarro i Ferrando. 1aBerlin ;aBoston : bDe Gruyter Mouton, c[2019] 4c©2019  a1 online resource (VI, 381 p.)  atextbtxt2rdacontent  acomputerbc2rdamedia  aonline resourcebcr2rdacarrier  atext filebPDF2rda0 aApplications of Cognitive Linguistics [ACL] ;v3900tFrontmatter -- tContents -- tMetaphor analysis in discourse. Introduction -- tPart I: Metaphor and knowledge configuration in discourse -- tSome consequences of a multi-level view of metaphor -- tCross-cultural semantic and pragmatic profiling of emotion words. Regulation and expression of anger in Spanish and German -- tMetaphors and evaluation in popular economic discourse on trade wars -- tTransdiscursive term transformation: The evidence from cognitive discursive research of the term ‘virus’ -- tMetaphor in grammar: Mapping across syntactic domains -- tMetaphors in the digital world: The case of metaphorical frames in ‘Facebook’ and ‘Amazon’ -- tMetaphorical conceptualization in the Euromaidan discourse -- tPart II: Consciousness in metaphor usage -- tDeliberate metaphors and embodied simulation -- tDeliberate metaphors in Buddhist teachings about meditation -- tUsing deliberate metaphor in discourse: Native vs. non-native text production -- tGeorge Ridpath’s use of metaphor, metonymy and metaphtonymy during the Peace Campaign (1710–1713) of the War of the Spanish Succession -- tPart III: Metaphor analysis in multimodal discourse -- tSpatialization of abstract concepts in cartoons. A case study of verbo-pictorial image-schematic metaphors -- tAnalyzing metaphor in film: Some conceptual challenges -- tTransmodality in metaphors: TIDES in Spanish social protest movements -- tVisual metaphors in economic discourse. An analysis of the interaction of conventional and novel visual metaphors in The Economist -- tDevelopments in multimodal metaphor studies: A response to Górska, Coëgnarts, Porto & Romano, and Muelas-Gil -- tSubject Index0 arestricted accessuhttp://purl.org/coar/access_right/c_16ecfonline access with authorization2star  aThis volume takes up the challenge of surveying the present state of a variety of approaches to the identification, analysis and interpretation of metaphor across communication channels, situational contexts, genres and social spheres. It reflects three foremost trends of present metaphor research, namely the communicative approach, the cognitive modelling approach and the multimodality approach. These trends are considered as areas of research emerging on the ground of the Conceptual Metaphor Theory, initiated by Lakoff. The book intends to show their concomitances as well as mark their diversifying paths. The aim is to bring about and make apparent the many connections among assumingly different trends stemming from CMT. Whereas discrepancies between communicative and conceptual perspectives might seem irredeemable, the book emphasizes and claims that the background framework of CMT provides a solid foundation for collaboration and mutual influence. Consequently, the analysis of metaphor usage in context may provide insights for cognitive modelling proposals. The analysis of cognitive configuration of conceptual domains may, in turn, illuminate our understanding of communicative decisions in discourse. The integration of multimodal metaphor analysis puts forward the idea that diverse modal manifestations of metaphor reveal the symbiosis between communicative and cognitive stances. The various subject areas and methodologies illuminate the scene of current research in the field. The poignant contributions open far reaching avenues into the realm of human thought and discourse.  aMode of access: Internet via World Wide Web.  aIn English.0 aDescription based on online resource; title from PDF title page (publisher's Web site, viewed 21. Jun 2021) 0aMetaphor. 4aDiskurs. 4aKognitive Linguistik. 4aMetapher. 7aLANGUAGE ARTS & DISCIPLINES / Linguistics / General.2bisacsh  aCognitive Linguistics, Human Communication, Metaphor, Discourse.1 aApresjan, Valentina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aBurdina, Olga, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCai, Dongman, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCoëgnarts, Maarten, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCuberos, Rocío, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aCuccio, Valentina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDeignan, Alice, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aDilai, Marianna, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aEsbrí-Blasco, Montserrat, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aFerrando, Ignasi Navarro i, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aForceville, Charles, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGirón-García, Carolina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aGórska, Elżbieta, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aIsaeva, Ekaterina, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aKövecses, Zoltán, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aMuelas-Gil, María, econtributor.4ctb4https://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/ctb1 aNavarro i Ferrando, Ignasi, eeditor.4edt4http://id.loc.gov/vocabulary/relators/edt1 aOster, Ulr